Narrative Log

Dev Log - 2026-05-08

This was a boundary day.

Not a flashy feature day, and not really a polish day either. It was the kind of day where the important work is making the system harder to misunderstand. The center of gravity was the obsidian context request-plan path: Codexify moved from loose context handling toward a more explicit directive flow, where the backend consumes structured context instructions instead of treating them as ambient prompt material.

That shift ran through the prompt layer, the context broker, the directive resolver, the completion service, and the token vocabulary that binds them together. The real change was not just that the code path exists now. It is that the system has a more legible way to say what kind of context it is processing and why. That lowers the chance of hidden behavior drifting in under a vague name.

The work was backed by tests, which matters here because this is contract work, not cosmetics. The new coverage exercises prompt assembly, directive resolution, broker command handling, and completion semantics so the behavior is pinned down where it can actually be enforced.

A second thread ran in parallel: bounded execution and runtime truth. The chat worker now preserves bounded tool-loop metadata instead of letting that state flatten or disappear, and the surrounding route and worker tests were extended accordingly. That is the sort of change that does not announce itself as a product feature, but it improves the quality of every later diagnosis. If the system can carry the right metadata through execution, it can also explain itself better when something goes wrong.

The other significant arc was the graph-write runtime boundary. The compose path now treats graph writes as default-off, with a dedicated factory/config seam and test coverage around that boundary. That is a small but important discipline move. It means the release story does not accidentally drift into implying graph-write availability where the current supported path does not promise it. In a system like this, explicit gating is part of honesty.

The rest of the day was cleanup that mattered because the higher-level changes needed a clean base. There were parseability repairs after merge artifacts, a worker packaging fix for the coding result path, a model-selection trace helper repair, a duplicate `if` artifact removal, and a frontend import correction. None of those are headline changes by themselves, but each one removes a source of false confidence or runtime ambiguity.

So the deeper change today was not expansion. It was correction.

Codexify now carries more of its own contract in code and tests, less in implied behavior. The system is a little more truthful about what it can consume, what it preserves, and what it refuses by default. That makes the next proof run more meaningful, because the underlying runtime is less likely to lie by omission.



